'''Harmon Clayton Killebrew''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|<U+02C8>|k|<U+026A>|l|<U+0268>|b|r|u<U+02D0>}}; June 29, 1936&nbsp;&ndash; May 17, 2011), nicknamed "'''Killer'''" and "'''Hammerin' Harmon'''", was an American professional baseball [[first baseman]], [[third baseman]], and [[left fielder]]. During his 22-year career, he played for the Washington Senators, a team which later became the [[Minnesota Twins]], and the [[Kansas City Royals]]. When he retired, he was second only to [[Babe Ruth]] in [[American League]] (AL) [[home run]]s and was the AL career leader in home runs by a [[right-handed]] batter (since broken by [[Alex Rodriguez]]).<ref name=Goldstein>{{cite news|last=Goldstein|first=Richard|title=Harmon Killebrew, Twins<U+2019> Hall of Fame Slugger, Dies at 74|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/18/sports/baseball/harmon-killebrew-twins-hall-of-fame-slugger-dies-at-74.html?partner=rss&emc=rss|accessdate=May 17, 2011|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref> He was inducted into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1984.

Killebrew was a [[wikt:stocky|stocky]] {{convert|5|ft|11|in|m|abbr=on}}, 210-pound (95.3&nbsp;kg) hitter with a compact swing that generated tremendous power. He became one of the AL's most feared power hitters of the 1960s, hitting 40 home runs in a season eight times. In 1965, he played in the [[World Series]] with the Minnesota Twins, who lost to the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]]. His finest season was 1969, when he hit 49 home runs, recorded 140 [[runs batted in]] (RBI), and won the AL [[MLB Most Valuable Player award|Most Valuable Player Award]]. Killebrew led the league six times in home runs and three times in RBIs, and was named to eleven [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] teams.

With quick hands and exceptional upper-body strength, Killebrew was known not just for the frequency of his home runs but also for their distance. He hit the longest measured home runs at [[Metropolitan Stadium|Minnesota's Metropolitan Stadium]], {{convert|520|ft|m|abbr=on}}, and [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Baltimore's Memorial Stadium]], {{convert|471|ft|m|abbr=on}}, and was the first of just four batters to hit a baseball over the [[left field]] roof at [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Detroit's Tiger Stadium]]. Despite his nicknames and his powerful style of play, Killebrew was considered by his colleagues to be a quiet, kind man. Asked once what hobbies he had, Killebrew replied, "Just washing the dishes, I guess."<ref name="SIHeilman1">{{Cite journal|last=Heilman|first=Barbara|date=April 8, 1963|accessdate=July 7, 2008|journal=[[Sports Illustrated]]|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1074683/1/index.htm|title=Out Of The Park On A Half Swing}}</ref>

After retiring from baseball, Killebrew became a television broadcaster for several baseball teams from 1976 to 1988, and also served as a hitting instructor for the [[Oakland Athletics]]. He also divorced and remarried during this time, moving to Arizona in 1990 and chairing the Harmon Killebrew Foundation. Killebrew was diagnosed with [[esophageal cancer]] in December 2010, and died five months later.

==Early life==
Born in [[Payette, Idaho|Payette]], Idaho, Harmon Killebrew was youngest of four children to Harmon Clayton, Sr. and Katherine Pearl (May) Killebrew. His father, a painter and [[Sheriffs in the United States|sheriff]], was a member of an undefeated [[Millikin College]] [[American football|football]] team who was later named an [[All-America]]n under eventual [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]] coach [[Greasy Neale]].<ref name="Porter807">[[#Porter|Porter]], p. 807.</ref><ref name="Thielman132">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 132.</ref> According to family legend, Harmon Killebrew's grandfather was the strongest man in the [[Union Army]], winning every available [[Wrestling weight classes|heavyweight wrestling]] championship.<ref name="Thielman132"/> Clayton encouraged Harmon and his brothers to stay active in various sports before his sudden death in 1953 at age 59.<ref name="Thielman132"/>

As a child, Harmon played baseball at [[Walter Johnson]] Memorial Field, named after the [[Baseball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] pitcher who spent part of his childhood in Idaho.<ref name="Thielman131">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 131.</ref> He worked as a farmworker in his youth, where he lifted 10-gallon milk cans, each can weighing about 95&nbsp;lb (43&nbsp;kg).<ref name=Goldstein/> Killebrew earned 12 [[Letterman (sports)|letters]] in various sports and was named an [[All-America#High school sports|All-American]] [[quarterback]] at [[Payette High School]]; his uniform number was later retired by the school.<ref name="Porter807"/><ref name="Thielman134">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 134.</ref> He was offered an [[athletic scholarship]] by the [[Oregon Ducks|University of Oregon]], but opted to attend the [[College of Idaho]] instead.<ref name="Porter8078">[[#Porter|Porter]], pp. 807<U+2013>808.</ref>

In the early 1950s, [[List of United States Senators from Idaho|Idaho Senator]] [[Herman Welker]] told Washington Senators owner [[Clark Griffith]] about Killebrew, who was hitting for an .847 [[batting average]] for a [[semi-professional]] baseball team at the time.<ref name="Thielman131"/><ref name="Porter808">[[#Porter|Porter]], p. 808.</ref> Griffith told his [[Farm team|farm]] director [[Ossie Bluege]] about the tip and Bluege flew to Idaho to watch Killebrew play.<ref name="Thielman133">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 133.</ref> The [[Boston Red Sox]] also expressed interest but Bluege succeeded in signing him to a $50,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|50000|1954|r=0}}}} today) contract on June 19, 1954.<ref name="Thielman134"/><ref name="Porter808"/><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Senators Pay $50,000 To First Bonus Player|date=June 20, 1954|page=3}}</ref>

==Professional baseball career==
===Washington Senators===
Killebrew signed his contract under [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB)'s [[Bonus Rule]], which required that he spend two full seasons on the major league roster.<ref name="Porter808"/> Making his major league debut four days after signing and six days from his 18th birthday (becoming the youngest active player in the majors at the time), Killebrew was called on to run for [[Clyde Vollmer]], who had drawn a [[bases loaded]] [[base on balls|walk]] off of [[Chicago White Sox]] starter [[Jack Harshman]] while [[pinch hitting]] for Senators [[relief pitcher|reliever]] [[Chuck Stobbs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195406230.shtml|title=June 23, 1954, Senators at White Sox Box Score and Play by Play|work=[[Baseball-Reference]]|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=May 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=BBRef>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/k/killeha01.shtml|title=Harmon Killebrew Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> On August 23, 1954, Killebrew made his first start in the second game of a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] against the [[Philadelphia Athletics]], hitting two [[single (baseball)|singles]] and a [[double (baseball)|double]] as the Senators won the game, 10<U+2013>3.<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Shirley|last=Povich|title=Kid Killebrew Shines at Bat in Bow as Nat|magazine=[[The Sporting News]]|date=September 1, 1954|page=6}}</ref> A year and one day after making his major league debut, Killebrew hit his first major league home run on June 24, 1955 in the 5th inning off [[Detroit Tigers]] starter [[Billy Hoeft]], five days shy of his 19th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS1/WS1195506240.shtml|title=June 24, 1955, Tigers at Senators Play by Play and Box Score|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=May 19, 2011}}</ref> In his first two seasons, Killebrew [[strikeout|struck out]] 34 times in only 93 [[at bat]]s, contributing to a .215 batting average with four [[home run]]s.<ref name="Porter808"/> Killebrew also had defensive difficulties at [[Third baseman|third base]], where he played behind veteran [[Eddie Yost]].<ref name="Porter808"/>

[[File:Harmon Killebrew 1959.png|thumb|170px|left|Killebrew with the Senators in 1959.]]
When Killebrew's bonus period expired in 1956, he was sent to the Senators' [[Minor league baseball|minor league]] affiliate in [[Charlotte Hornets (baseball)|Charlotte]] of the [[Southern League (baseball)|South Atlantic League]].<ref name="RetiredNumbers">{{Cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/min/history/killebrew.jsp|title=Minnesota Twins Retired Numbers <U+2013> 3: Harmon Killebrew|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=July 23, 2008}}</ref> He returned to the majors in early May. On May 29, after being forced into action when regular [[second baseman]] [[Pete Runnels]] was injured early in the game, Killebrew hit two home runs in the game, including only the second ball ever hit over a wire barrier in [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Memorial Stadium]]'s center field.<ref name="Retro1956HK">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1956/Ikillh1020031956.htm|title=The 1956 WAS A Regular Season Batting Log for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=[[Retrosheet]]|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Thielman136">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 136.</ref> Killebrew had a .115 average through June 16, and as a result was sent back to Charlotte; he finished the season there with a .325 batting average and 15 home runs in 70 games.<ref name="Retro1956HK"/><ref name="BRMinors">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=killeb001har|title=Harmon Killebrew Minor League Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref> Killebrew spent most of the 1957 season with the [[Southern Association]]'s [[Chattanooga Lookouts]], where he hit a league-high 29 home runs with 101 RBIs and was named to the All-Star Game.<ref name="BRMinors"/><ref name="Thielman137">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 137.</ref> While in Chattanooga, Killebrew became the only player to hit a home run over the center field wall at [[Engel Stadium]], {{convert|471|ft|m}} from home plate.<ref name="Murrell">{{Cite web|url=http://www.idahopress.com/special/?sr=4&sra=4537|title=Harmon Killebrew: Baseball's killer|last=Murrell|first=I. C|work=[[The Idaho Press-Tribune]]|accessdate=July 13, 2008|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080618193733/http://www.idahopress.com/special/?sr=4&sra=4537|archivedate=June 18, 2008}}</ref> In 1958, he was briefly promoted to [[Indianapolis Indians|Indianapolis]] of the [[American Association (20th century)|American Association]] but struggled and was sent back to Chattanooga for most of the season.<ref name="Thielman137"/> Killebrew finished the season with 38 games played in Indianapolis and 86 in Chattanooga, where he hit .308 with 17 home runs.<ref name="BRMinors"/> He also played a combined 22 games for the Senators in 1957 and 1958.<ref name="BBRef"/>

[[Calvin Griffith]] took over the Senators after his uncle [[Clark Griffith]] died in 1955, and decided Killebrew was ready to become the Senators' regular third baseman. Griffith traded the 32-year-old Eddie Yost to the [[Detroit Tigers]] on December 6, 1958, and Killebrew became the starting third baseman.<ref name="Porter808"/><ref name="BBRefYost">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/y/yosted01.shtml|title=Eddie Yost Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 28, 2008}}</ref> From May 1 to May 17, he had five multi-home run games and his first five-RBI game on May 12.<ref name="Porter808"/> With 28 home runs by mid-season, he started the [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|first 1959 All-Star Game]] and was a reserve in [[1959 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|the second]]. Killebrew attracted so much attention in Washington that he was visited by President of the United States [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], who frequently attended games,<ref name="Allen76">[[#Allen|Allen]], p. 76.</ref> and Griffith turned down a $500,000 offer for Killebrew from the [[Cincinnati Reds]].<ref name="Allen76"/> Killebrew finished the season with 42 home runs to tie for the [[List of Major League Baseball home run champions|American League lead]]; it also tied the Senator's single-season record set by his teammate [[Roy Sievers]] two years earlier.<ref name="Porter808"/><ref name="DigestClubRecords">{{Cite journal|month=June|year=2003|accessdate=July 20, 2008|journal=[[Baseball Digest]]|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCI/is_6_62/ai_100961691|title=Club home run leaders <U+2013> Season}}</ref> Although 1959 proved his breakout season, he was ineligible for the [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]] because of his previous sparse experience. Instead, the award went to teammate [[Bob Allison]].<ref name="Thielman143">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 143.</ref>

Killebrew was bothered by injury early in the 1960 season. In March, he had surgery for nasal irritation,<ref>{{cite news|title=Killebrew to Undergo Knife|work=[[Gadsden Times]]|date=March 27, 1960|page=6|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KggpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1tUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4333,2674224}}</ref> and a recurring [[hamstring]] injury caused him to miss most of May.<ref>{{cite news|title=...To Complete the Report|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 12, 1960|page=D3}}</ref> On his return, he remained in the lineup for the rest of the season, finishing the year with 31 home runs in 124 games.<ref name="BBRef"/><ref name="RetiredNumbers"/> Killebrew's arrival and home runs did little to improve the Senators' record, as they finished in the [[first division (baseball)|second division]] of the American League every year he played in Washington, including four years in last place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/|title=Minnesota Twins History & Encyclopedia|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 29, 2008}}</ref> Following the 1960 season, the Senators moved to Minnesota and became the [[Minnesota Twins]].

===Minnesota Twins===
====1961<U+2013>1965====
For the franchise's first year in Minnesota, Killebrew was named [[Major League Baseball Team Captains|team captain]] by [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Cookie Lavagetto]].<ref name="Thielman16">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 16.</ref> He responded by hitting 46 home runs, breaking the franchise record he had tied two years earlier.<ref name="DigestClubRecords"/> Among his other accomplishments over the course of the season, Killebrew accumulated a team-leading 122 RBIs, achieved a career-best batting average of .288 and had a [[slugging percentage]] of over .600 for the only time in his career. In addition, he had a career-high seven [[triple (baseball)|triples]], tying for the team lead, and led his team in runs, total bases and walks.<ref name=BBRef/><ref name="RetiredNumbers"/> On June 12, 1961, Killebrew had the only five-hit game of his career in a losing effort by the Twins.<ref name="RetroHKTop">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/K/PX_killh102.htm|title=Top Performances for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 20, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew was named to both 1961 All-Star games. He did not play in the second game, but in the [[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|first game]], he hit a [[pinch hitter|pinch hit]] home run in the sixth inning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/NLS/NLS196107110.shtml|title=July 11, 1961 All-Star Game Play-By-Play|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref> After the season ended, Killebrew took part in a home run hitting contest with [[Jim Gentile]] and [[Roger Maris]], whose 61 home runs that year broke the single-season record; Killebrew hit 20 to win the contest.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Xt9iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VTAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5145,2486362|title=Killebrew Puts Maris In Shade In Homer Derby|work=[[Lewiston Morning Tribune]]|date=October 16, 1961|page=6}}</ref>

After his seven-triple season, his speed began to decrease and he could no longer regularly score triples due to pulling his [[Quadriceps femoris muscle|quadriceps]] during the 1962 season.<ref name="Thielman146">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 146.</ref> Killebrew moved to left field, where he started off the season slowly. He hit under .200 in both April and June, and because of this Killebrew was not selected to play in either 1962 All-Star Game, the last season he was not named an All-Star before 1972.<ref name="BBRef"/><ref name="Retro1962HKSplit">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1962/Jkillh1020091962.htm|title=The 1962 MIN A Batting Splits for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 15, 2008}}</ref> On July 18 in a game against the [[Cleveland Indians]], Killebrew and [[Bob Allison]] became the first teammates since 1890 to hit [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slams]] in the same inning as the Twins scored 11 runs in the first.<ref name="RetiredNumbers"/><ref name="RetroHK2GS">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1962/B07180MIN1962.htm|title=Minnesota Twins 14, Cleveland Indians 3|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 26, 2008}}</ref> Over the course of the season, Killebrew hit 48 home runs, 126 RBIs, and had 107 [[base on balls|walks]], all career highs at the time.<ref name="BBRef"/> No one else in the AL managed even 40 home runs and he also led the league in RBIs.<ref name="BBRef1962leaders">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL_1962_t.shtml|title=1962 American League Expanded Leaderboards|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 15, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew's 48 home runs also broke the franchise record for the second year in a row.<ref name="DigestClubRecords"/> Not all of his stats were positive; Killebrew's batting average dropped from .288 in 1961 to .243 and he struck out a career-worst 142 times, leading the AL.<ref name="BBRef"/>

Killebrew's efforts were rewarded in 1963 when he agreed to a contract for about $40,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|40000|1963|r=0}}}} today).<ref>{{cite news|title=Harmon Killebrew Okays Record Senators' Pact|work=[[The Hartford Courant]]|date=February 18, 1963|page=18A}}</ref> He started the season off slowly, and he missed the second half of April and early May due to a right knee injury that was slow to heal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Twins Bench Killebrew and .105 Bat|work=Chicago Tribune|page=B1|date=April 16, 1963}}</ref> Killebrew continued his hitting prowess for the Twins upon his return, and at one point led them on a six-game winning streak.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yt1QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VM8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=6758,6215550|first=Jim|last=Hackleman|title=Killebrew on Hit Spree|work=[[The Portsmouth Times]]|page=11|date=June 29, 1963}}</ref> On September 21, Killebrew hit three home runs in a game for the only time in his career in the first game of a doubleheader against the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref name="RetroHKTop"/><ref name="RetroHK3HR">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1963/B09211BOS1963.htm|title=Minnesota Twins 13, Boston Red Sox 4 (1)|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 20, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew finished the season with a .258 batting average, 45 home runs, and 96 RBI, and led the league in home runs and [[slugging percentage]] (.555).<ref name=BBRef/> He had surgery on his troublesome right knee after the season ended.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lc1eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xDIMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6095,2235303|title=Harmon Killebrew Has Knee Surgery|work=Lewiston Morning Tribune|date=December 13, 1963|page=14}}</ref>

Having played left field for the previous three years with a below-average throwing arm, the additional complication of Killebrew's knee surgery necessitated a move to the infield. For the remainder of his career, he played only 19 games in the outfield.<ref name="BBRef"/><ref name="Thielman146"/><ref name="Thielman145">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 145.</ref> He finished the 1964 season with a .270 batting average, 49 home runs, and 111 RBI; he led the AL in home runs for the third consecutive year.<ref name="BBRef"/>

The Twins finally won the [[American League pennant winners 1901<U+2013>68|American League pennant]] during the 1965 season. On July 11, the day before the All-Star break, defending AL champion Yankees had a one-run lead over the Twins going into the bottom of the 9th inning, but Killebrew hit a two-run home run for the win.<ref name="Thielman128130">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], pp. 128<U+2013>130.</ref> Two days later, Killebrew started the All-Star Game at his home field, [[Metropolitan Stadium]], and hit a game-tying two-run home run, erasing what had been a 5<U+2013>0 [[National League]] lead.<ref name="Allen79">[[#Allen|Allen]], p. 79.</ref> Elected to play first base on his fifth All-Star team, Killebrew became the first player in All-Star game history to be elected at three different positions, having previously been selected to play third base (1959 and 1961) and left field (1963 and 1964).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/twins/122004519.html|title=Killebrew was 'Paul Bunyan with a uniform on'|first=Lavelle E.|last=Neal III|date=May 18, 2011|work=[[Star Tribune]]|accessdate=May 18, 2011}}</ref>

Killebrew drove in the tying or winning run seven times in 1965 before suffering an injury on August 2.<ref name="Thielman102">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], p. 102.</ref> During a game against the Orioles, Twins third baseman [[Rich Rollins]] made a poor throw to first and while trying to save the play, Killebrew collided with the runner and [[Joint dislocation|dislocated]] his elbow, putting him out of action until mid-September.<ref name="Retro19650802">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1965/B08020MIN1965.htm|title=Minnesota Twins 6, Baltimore Orioles 5|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=June 29, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Retro1965HK">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1965/Ikillh1020121965.htm|title=The 1965 MIN A Regular Season Batting Log for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=June 29, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Thielman169170">[[#Thielman|Thielman]], pp. 169<U+2013>170.</ref> Despite his absence, the Twins had a win-loss record of 28<U+2013>19 and even extended their first place lead.<ref name="Thielman102"/><ref name="BBRef1965MinSched">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/1965_sched.shtml|title=1965 Minnesota Twins Schedule|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 29, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew ended the regular season with 25 home runs and 75 RBI, his lowest numbers in a full season due to the injury.<ref name="BBRef"/> In the [[1965 World Series]] against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], Killebrew and [[Zoilo Versalles]] led the Twins with .286 batting averages, and Killebrew hit a home run off [[Don Drysdale]] in Game 4. Overall, Minnesota was shut out in three games and the Dodgers won the series in seven games.<ref name="BBRef1965WS">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1965_WS.shtml|title=1965 World Series <U+2013> LAD vs. MIN|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref>

====1966<U+2013>1969====
At the start of the 1966 season, Killebrew scored few home runs; halfway through May, he had only hit two home runs, his lowest total at that point of a season since 1960, when he had missed the first two months of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=V-pTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DjkNAAAAIBAJ&pg=6135,3810983|title=Harmon Killebrew Off to Slow Start in Home Run Department|work=[[St. Joseph News-Press]]|date=May 19, 1966|page=6D}}</ref> He later increased his tally to 39 and finished the season with a .281 batting average and 110 RBIs. He led the AL with 103 walks and finished 4th in [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] (MVP) voting to [[Frank Robinson]], [[Brooks Robinson]], and [[Boog Powell]].<ref name="BBRef"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1966.shtml#ALmvp|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1966|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref>

During the 1967 season, Killebrew showed his ability to hit long home runs when, on June 3, 1967, he struck the longest home run recorded at Metropolitan Stadium, a shot that landed in the second deck of the bleachers.<ref name="Rushin1956">[[#Rushin|Rushin]], pp. 195<U+2013>196.</ref> The Twins, led by Killebrew, were in the pennant race throughout the season, and had a one-game lead as the final two games of the season began against the [[Boston Red Sox]]. Having to win only once to clinch the pennant, Killebrew hit a home run in the first game and recorded two hits in each game, but Boston won twice and Minnesota finished in a second place tie with the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/1967_sched.shtml|title=1967 Minnesota Twins Schedule|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew finished the season with a .269 batting average and 113 RBIs, and led the AL with 44 home runs and 131 walks.<ref name="BBRef"/> He also finished a distant second in MVP voting to Boston's [[triple crown (baseball)|Triple Crown]] winner [[Carl Yastrzemski]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1967.shtml#ALmvp|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1967|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref>

Killebrew started the 1968 season in a different venue; he served as a prosecution witness in a case where his name was being used to sell stocks in Idaho, unknown to him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4KVfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=WDIMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5853,1596682|title=Killebrew Testifies at Boise Fraud Trial Year|work=Lewiston Morning Tribune|page=15|date=April 10, 1968}}</ref> Despite this, the season was unsuccessful for Killebrew, whose batting average barely passed .200 most of the year; after a strong start, he hit below .200 in both May and June and his average stood at .204 with 13 home runs going into the all-star break.<ref name="Retro1968Split">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1968/Jkillh1020151968.htm|title=The 1968 MIN A Batting Splits for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 1, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Retro1968HK">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1968/Ikillh1020151968.htm|title=The 1968 MIN A Regular Season Batting Log for Harmon Killebrew|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 1, 2008}}</ref> Even so, he was selected as the starting first baseman in the All-Star Game and Killebrew stated that, owing to his poor start, he was "surprised" and "embarrassed" by the selection.<ref>{{cite news|title=Killebrew Finds Choice Surprise|first=Jim|last=Elliot|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|page=C1|date=June 28, 1968}}</ref> In the All-Star Game itself, he stretched for a ball while playing first base and slipped on the [[Reliant Astrodome|Astrodome]] turf, rupturing his left medial hamstring.<ref name="Allen79"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1968/B07090NLS1968.htm|title=National League 1, American League 0|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 1, 2008}}</ref><ref name="Armour192">[[#Armour|Armour]], p. 192.</ref> At the time, the injury was considered career-threatening, but after missing about six weeks, he returned to limited action in September.<ref name="Armour192"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Killebrew Out for 6-8 Weeks With Injury|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=D18|date=July 11, 1968}}</ref>

After enduring seven months of rehabilitation for his injury, Killebrew remained in pain but rebounded to have his best season in 1969.<ref name="Allen79" /> On July 5, Killebrew set a career-high with six RBIs in a game against the [[Oakland Athletics]].<ref name="RetroHKTop"/><ref name="RetroHK6RBI">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1969/B07050MIN1969.htm|title=Minnesota Twins 13, Oakland 1|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> That personal best lasted barely two months: on September 7 he hit a three-run home run and a grand slam for seven RBIs, all in the first two innings, to defeat the Athletics again.<ref name="RetroHKTop"/><ref name="RetroHK7RBI">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1969/B09070OAK1969.htm|title=Minnesota Twins 16, Oakland Athletics 4|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew led the best offense in the league and rookie manager [[Billy Martin]]'s Twins won the new [[American League West]] division as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/MIN/1969.shtml|title=1969 Minnesota Twins Batting, Pitching, and Fielding Statistics|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>

For the season, Killebrew set career highs in RBIs, runs, walks and [[on-base percentage]], tied his career high with 49 home runs, and even registered eight of his 19 career stolen bases, en route to winning his only [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]].<ref name="Allen79"/> He led the AL in home runs, RBIs, on-base percentage, walks, and intentional walks and knocked in the winning run 20 times while playing in all 162 games.<ref name="BBRef"/><ref name="Allen80">[[#Allen|Allen]], p. 80.</ref> As of 2011, Killebrew's home run, RBI, and walk totals from 1969 remain team records,<ref name="RetiredNumbers"/> and his 145 walks are tied for the 20th highest single season total in MLB history and 7th highest for a right-handed batter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/BB_season.shtml|title=Single-Season Leaders & Records for Bases on Balls|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=May 18, 2011}}</ref> In the [[1969 American League Championship Series]], the [[Baltimore Orioles]] used their pitching staff, the best in the league, to defeat Minnesota and win the series three games to none.<ref name="Armour192"/> Baltimore avoided Killebrew by walking him six times in the three games to avoid pitching to him, which was as many times as they walked the rest of the Twins team.<ref name="BBRef1969ALCS">{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1969_ALCS.shtml|title=1969 AL Championship Series <U+2013> BAL vs. MIN|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref>

====1970<U+2013>1974====
After his MVP season, Killebrew signed a new contract with the Twins worth $90,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|90000|1970|r=0}}}} today).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tctNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2087,6127662|title=Frank Robinson, Killebrew Sign Up|work=[[The Free Lance-Star]]|date=February 26, 1970|page=5}}</ref> He was set to lead a team that had undergone a lot of change; Killebrew was one of only four Twins remaining from the 1965 pennant-winning club.<ref name="Armour193">[[#Armour|Armour]], p. 193.</ref> He spent most of the season's first half continuing his success, and found Baltimore's [[Brooks Robinson]] rivalling him for the third base spot during the All-Star voting process; the two were neck-and-neck throughout.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=yX4sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6MwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4653,3329896|title=Harmon, Brooks Battle For Third|work=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal]]|page=9|date=June 20, 1970}}</ref> He continued his success through the second half of the year, and at season's end Killebrew had hit 41 home runs with 113 RBIs and finished third in MVP voting behind teammate [[Tony Oliva]] and Baltimore's [[Boog Powell]], who won the award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1970.shtml#ALmvp|title=Baseball Awards Voting for 1970|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref> The Twins again faced Powell and the Orioles in the [[1970 American League Championship Series]], a rematch of the previous season. The Twins were again swept, though Killebrew's performance improved as he hit two home runs in three games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1970_ALCS.shtml|title=1970 AL Championship Series <U+2013> BAL vs. MIN|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=July 4, 2008}}</ref>

Killebrew reached the 40 home runs for the final time in 1970 and also made his last appearance in the postseason. His contract continued to grow in value though, and before the 1971 season began he was awarded the first $100,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|100000|1971|r=0}}}} today) contract in Twins' history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9k0fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mdEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=731,4628288|title=$100,000 Pact For Killebrew|work=[[Daytona Beach Morning Journal]]|page=7|date=February 17, 1971}}</ref> Killebrew appeared in his last All-Star Game in 1971, hitting a two-run home run off [[Ferguson Jenkins]] to provide the margin of victory for the AL.<ref name="BBRef"/><ref name="Retro1971AS">{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1971/B07130ALS1971.htm|title=American League 6, National League 4|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 6, 2008}}</ref> He finished the season with a .254 batting average, 114 walks, 119 RBI, the latter two of which led the league, and 28 home runs.<ref name="BBRef"/> Killebrew hit his 498th home run on June 22, 1971, but a sprained right toe made his run to milestone number 500 a slow one. He hit number 499 more than a month later and finally hit number 500 off a [[Mike Cuellar]] slow [[curveball]] in the first inning of an August 10 home game; at the time, he was the 10th player in history to hit 500 home runs. He then wasted no time in hitting number 501, knocking a Cuellar [[fastball]] over the fences later in the same game.<ref name="Allen80"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1971/B08100MIN1971.htm|title=Baltimore Orioles 4, Minnesota Twins 3|publisher=Retrosheet|accessdate=July 6, 2008}}</ref>

{{MLBBioRet
|Align  = Right
|Image  = TwinsRetired3.png
|Name   = Harmon Killebrew
|Number = 3
|Team   = Minnesota Twins
|Year   = 1975
}}
In 1972, Killebrew showed signs of slowing down. He missed his first All-Star Game since 1962, but instead of expressing disappointment in his streak ending, he noted that Twins shortstop [[Danny Thompson (baseball)|Danny Thompson]] should have had the opportunity to play instead; Thompson mentioned the same thing about Killebrew.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=43chAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mokFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3789,2028718|title=Killebrew Not Upset Over Star Deletion|work=[[Schenectady Gazette]]|page=16|date=July 25, 1972}}</ref> Despite not making the team, Killebrew's home run total continued to climb, and by the end of July he had [[Jimmie Foxx]] and [[Mickey Mantle]] career marks in his sights;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=E29kAAAAIBAJ&sjid=b30NAAAAIBAJ&pg=2616,1422721|title=Harmon eyes Foxx and Mantle|work=[[The Calgary Herald]]|page=17|date=July 24, 1972}}</ref> he went on to pass both in August. Killebrew finished the season with a .231 batting average, 26 home runs, and 74 RBIs.<ref name="BBRef"/> There were questions about Killebrew's health as the 1973 season began, as he had surgery twice during the offseason to fix leg problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gO1HAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4v8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=734,3526347|title=Health of Killebrew, Oliva Keys To Twins Chances in AL West|work=[[The Morning Record]]|page=13|date=March 26, 1973}}</ref> He played through the first half of the season, but an injury to his left knee on June 25 sidelined him. A month later, the injury had not cleared up, and he underwent surgery to remove some torn cartilage; he did not return to the lineup until mid-September.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oZ1fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xDEMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4318,5717330|title=Surgery Sidelines Harmon Killebrew For Six Weeks|work=Lewiston Morning Tribune|page=14|date=July 24, 1973}}</ref> Killebrew only played in 69 games that season, hitting five home runs.<ref name="BBRef"/>

Fully recovered for the 1974 season, Killebrew made his mark early on, hitting two home runs in a May 5 match against the [[Detroit Tigers]]; the second was career home run number 550.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=RFVRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4DMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1206,954437|title=Harmon Killebrew Still Has His Big Moments|work=The Evening News|page=8B|date=May 6, 1974}}</ref> In his honor, the Twins held a Harmon Killebrew Day in August, where it was announced that they would retire his number; Killebrew responded by leading the Twins to a 5&ndash;4 victory over the Orioles.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=100aAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-ygEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7340,1829833|title=Killebrew Says Thanks With Bat|work=[[The Milwaukee Journal]]|date=August 12, 1974|page=12}}</ref> He finished the season with a .222 batting average, 13 home runs, and 54 RBIs.<ref name="BBRef"/> In December 1974, he was given the option of staying with the Twins as a coach and batting instructor, managing the AAA [[Tacoma Twins]], or being released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vVMsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=B80EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5512,3194951|title=Griffith Offers 3 Options|work=Spartanburg Herald-Journal|page=9|date=December 13, 1974}}</ref> He chose to be released, ending his 21-season tenure with the Twins.

===Kansas City Royals===
On January 24, 1975, eight days after getting his release from the Twins, Killebrew signed a one-year contract with the [[Kansas City Royals]]. During his return to Minnesota in early May, the Twins formally retired his No. 3 jersey. In that game, Killebrew hit a home run against his former teammates and received a standing ovation from the crowd.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SFsfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YdQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3087,2437691|title=Killebrew Connects in Return to Minn.|work=[[The Nevada Daily Mail]]|page=8|date=May 5, 1975}}</ref> In 106 games with the Royals, he had a batting average of .199, 14 home runs, and 44 RBIs.<ref name=BBRef/> At the end of the season, the Royals decided to release Killebrew.<ref name="Allen81">[[#Allen|Allen]], p. 81.</ref> In March 1976, he formally announced his retirement and stated that he would become an announcer and color commentator for Twins games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=t2RNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DfsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7267,729896|title=Harmon Killebrew Retires, Broadcasting Career Next|work=[[Lakeland Ledger]]|page=2B|date=March 4, 1976}}</ref>

