==Later life==
[[File:Harmon Killebrew.jpg|thumb|upright|Harmon Killebrew in 2007]]
Killebrew was first eligible for the Hall of Fame in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 1981|1981]] and received 239 votes, or 59.6% of the vote; 75% of the vote is required for induction.<ref name=bbhofvote>{{Cite web|url=http://baseballhall.org/hall-famers/bbwaa-voting/year?year=1981|title=Hall of Fame Votes By Player|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame|accessdate=July 5, 2008}}</ref> In [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 1982|1982]], Killebrew received 59.3% of the vote, taking a backseat to [[Hank Aaron]] and [[Frank Robinson]], who made it in their first year of eligibility.<ref name=bbhofvote/> After receiving 71.9% of the vote in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 1983|1983]], Killebrew said that not getting in that year was more difficult to accept than the previous two times, and asked "Why do the writers feel there only has to be a certain number inducted each time?"<ref>{{Cite journal|first=Patrick|last=Reusse|title=Killebrew Faces More Frustration|magazine=The Sporting News|date=January 31, 1983|page=43}}</ref> In [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 1984|1984]], Killebrew received 83.1% of the vote and was elected to the Hall in his fourth year of eligibility, joining [[Luis Aparicio]] and [[Don Drysdale]] as electees.<ref name=bbhofvote/>

Following his retirement, Killebrew was a television broadcaster for the Twins at [[WCCO-TV]] from 1976 to 1978, the Oakland Athletics from 1979 to 1982, the [[California Angels]] in 1983 and back with Minnesota from 1984 to 1988.<ref name="TwinsBroadcasters">{{Cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/min/history/broadcasters.jsp|title=Twins All-Time Broadcasters|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, L.P.|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name="BaseballHallCom">{{Cite web|url=http://community.baseballhall.org/page.aspx?pid=465|title=Baseball Hall of Fame <U+2013> Frick Voting <U+2013> Retired Broadcasters|publisher=National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Markoe515">[[#Markoe|Markoe]], p. 515.</ref> While with Oakland, he also served as a major- and minor-league hitting instructor.<ref name="hittinginstructor">{{Cite news|title=Uneasy Peace on Sox' Bench|first=Peter|last=Gammons|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=April 19, 1981}}</ref> In the late 1980s, Killebrew had financial problems. In July 1988, his house went into [[foreclosure]] and, in 1989, the ''[[Minneapolis Star Tribune]]'' reported that he had fallen $700,000 into debt.<ref name="Allen81"/><ref name="Kalb350">[[#Kalb|Kalb]], p. 350.</ref> He also divorced his first wife of over 30 years, Elaine, who he had married in 1955.<ref name="Kalb350"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Richard|last=Dozer|title=That's Harmon Killebrew, Washington Senators' 23 Year Old Home Run Hitter|work=Chicago Tribune|date=August 16, 1959|page=F20}}</ref> Soon after, Killebrew's health failed. In May 1990, he was rushed to the hospital with a [[pneumothorax|collapsed lung]] and damaged [[esophagus]].<ref name="Kalb351">[[#Kalb|Kalb]], p. 351.</ref> Together with a subsequent [[abscess]] and [[staph infection]], Killebrew endured three surgeries and nearly died. He used a wheelchair for some time post-surgery. By December 1990, his health was improved and he was remarried to Nita.<ref name="Allen81"/><ref name="Kalb351"/>

Killebrew was involved in a [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], Idaho insurance and securities business.<ref name="Markoe515"/> He moved to [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]], Arizona in 1990, where he chaired the Harmon Killebrew Foundation, which he created in 1998.<ref name="Markoe515"/><ref name="Foundation">{{Cite web|url=http://www.harmonkillebrewfoundation.org|title=Harmon Killebrew Foundation|publisher=The Lowertown Group|accessdate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> Killebrew founded the Danny Thompson Memorial Golf Tournament in 1977 with former [[Idaho]] [[United States Congress|congressman]] [[Ralph R. Harding|Ralph Harding]], which is played annually in late August in [[Sun Valley, Idaho]], and has donated more than $8.6&nbsp;million to [[leukemia]] and cancer research. Thompson was a Twins teammate who continued his major league career while suffering from [[leukemia]]; he died in December 1976 at the age of 29.<ref name="Thompson">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dannythompsonmemorial.com|title=Danny Thompson Memorial Golf Tournament|publisher=Danny Thompson Memorial Foundation|accessdate=August 22, 2008}}</ref>

On December 29, 2010, Killebrew announced that he had been diagnosed with [[esophageal cancer]] and started treatment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kare11.com/news/news_article.aspx?storyid=896819|title=Twins great Harmon Killebrew diagnosed with cancer|work=[[KARE]]|date=December 30, 2010|accessdate=December 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5969976|title=Harmon Killebrew says he has cancer|date=January 14, 2011|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref> On May 13, 2011, a Minnesota Twins press release reported he was ceasing treatment and entering [[hospice care]], because his illness had progressed beyond his doctors' expectation of cure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20110513&content_id=19005846&vkey=pr_min&fext=.jsp&c_id=min&tcid=fb-min-misc-20110513-killebrew|title=Statement from Harmon Killebrew|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 13, 2011|accessdate=May 13, 2011}}</ref> To honor Killebrew, the Twins wore their 1961 [[throwback uniform|throwback]] [[alternate jersey]]s at home for the remainder of the 2011 season;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.twins.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110514&content_id=19061044&c_id=min&vkey=notebook_min&notebook_id=19061052|title=Twins' vintage jerseys will honor Killebrew|publisher=MLB.com|author=Rhett Bollinger|date=May 14, 2011|accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref>; he was also honored by the [[Washington Nationals]], who hung a jersey with Killebrew's name and number 3 in their home dugout.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/post/nationals-twins-pay-tribute-to-harmon-killebrew/2011/05/16/AFJ5Yp4G_blog.html|first=Cindy|last=Boren|title=Nationals, Twins pay tribute to Harmon Killebrew|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=May 16, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2011}}</ref> Killebrew died on May 17, 2011 at his home in [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]], Arizona at the age of 74, a month and a half short of his 75th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=6559023|title=Harmon Killebrew dies at 74|publisher=ESPN|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=May 17, 2011}}</ref> Following his death, the Twins released a statement:

{{quote|text=No individual has ever meant more to the Minnesota Twins organization and millions of fans across Twins Territory than Harmon Killebrew. Harmon will long be remembered as one of the most prolific home run hitters in the history of the game and the leader of a group of players who helped lay the foundation for the long-term success of the Twins franchise and Major League Baseball in the Upper Midwest. However, more importantly Harmon's legacy will be the class, dignity and humility he demonstrated each and every day as a Hall of Fame-quality husband, father, friend, teammate and man.|sign=Twins' President David St. Peter|source=Star Tribune<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.naplesnews.com/news/2011/may/17/mlb-quotes-death-twins-great-harmon-killebrew/|title=Quotes about the death of Twins great Harmon Killebrew|work=[[Naples News]]|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>}}

==Character and legacy==
{{Quote box| quote ="Killebrew can knock the ball out of any park, including [[Yellowstone National Park|Yellowstone]]."|align=right |width=30%|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|source=<U+2014> [[Paul Richards (baseball)|Paul Richards]], [[Baltimore Orioles]] [[manager (baseball)|manager]], 1959.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/may/18/local/la-me-harmon-killebrew-20110518|title=Harmon Killebrew dies at 74; Hall of Famer was one of baseball's premier home-run hitters|first=Keith|last=Thursby|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 18, 2001|accessdate=July 2, 2011}}</ref>}}
Despite his nicknames and style of play, Killebrew was considered by his colleagues to be a quiet, kind man.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jim|last=Caple|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=caple_jim&id=6549955|title=Harmon Killebrew was a treasure|publisher=ESPN|date=May 17, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref> While still an active major leaguer, Killebrew became a [[Mormon]], and never smoked or drank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703509104576329251723756040.html|title=Modest 'Killer' Let Bat Do His Talking|first=Stephen|last=Miller|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=May 18, 2011|accessdate=May 19, 2011}}</ref> He was once asked in an interview what hobbies he had, to which he replied, "Just washing the dishes, I guess."<ref name="SIHeilman1"/> In his career, Killebrew hit 573 home runs, which as of 2011 is currently 11th all-time, 1,584 RBIs, 1,559 walks, which is currently 15th all-time, and he easily holds the all-time home run record among players born in the state of [[Idaho]] with 573; [[Vance Law]] is second with 71.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/bio/ID_born.shtml|title=Players by birthplace: Idaho Baseball Stats and Info|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=August 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/BB_career.shtml|title=Career Leaders & Records for Bases on Balls|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=May 18, 2011}}</ref> He also finished with the record of having the most plate appearances (9,831) in his career without a sacrifice hit (since broken by [[Frank Thomas (designated hitter)|Frank Thomas]] with 10,074 plate appearances).<ref name=BBRef/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/players/t/thomafr04.shtml|title=Frank Thomas Statistics and History|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>

[[File:MOA Killebrew Drive 080705.JPG|thumb|left|MOA entrance and Killebrew Drive]]
The street along the south side of the [[Mall of America]], the former site of Metropolitan Stadium, was named "Killebrew Drive" in his honor. Banners that hung above the Metrodome's outfield upper deck, resembling baseball cards, showed the retired numbers: Killebrew (3), [[Rod Carew]] (29), Tony Oliva (6), [[Kent Hrbek]] (14) and [[Kirby Puckett]] (34). In 1999, he was ranked 69th on The Sporting News list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players<ref>{{Cite journal|year=1999|month=April|title=Baseball's 100 Greatest Players|magazine=The Sporting News|pages=20|accessdate=July 3, 2008}}</ref> and was nominated as a finalist for Major League Baseball's All-Century Team.<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://static.espn.go.com/mlb/news/1999/1023/129008.html|title=All-Century Team final voting|accessdate=March 5, 2009|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=ESPN|date=October 23, 1999}}</ref> When the Twins moved into [[Target Field]] in 2010, Gate 3 on the southeast (centerfield) side of the stadium was named in his honor. There are also corresponding gates for the team's other retired numbers. Killebrew Canyon at [[Heavenly Mountain Resort]] is also named after the baseball star, who [[Alpine skiing|skied]] the outer limits of the resort after his retirement from baseball.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heavenly Resort turns 50|work=[[Reno Gazette]]|page=E1|date=November 13, 2005}}</ref>

Despite rumors that Killebrew was the player depicted in the [[Major League Baseball logo]], according to the creator, Jerry Dior, it was not patterned after Killebrew or any other specific player.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Man Behind the MLB Logo|first=David|last=Davis|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=October 23, 2008|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB122453063968851133.html|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=logo>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=13629819|title=Legend of MLB logo: Designer Says Not Killebrew|work=[[ABC News]]|first=Dave|last=Campbell|date=May 19, 2011|accessdate=June 30, 2011}}</ref> Killebrew is the model for the [[Major League Baseball Players Alumni Association]], an organization which Killebrew helped found in 1982.<ref name=logo/>

Killebrew was known as an all-around gentleman during his playing career. [[Reggie Jackson]] once said, "If Harmon Killebrew isn't the league's best player, I've never seen one. He's one of the greatest of all time."<ref name="Allen80"/> He was even noted as being kind to the umpires:

{{quote|text=The Killer was one of the most feared sluggers in baseball history, but he was also one of the nicest people ever to play the game. He was one of the few players who would go out of his way to compliment umpires on a good job, even if their calls went against him. I'd call a tough strike on him and he would turn around and say approvingly, "Good call." And he was the same way in the field. And he never did this to get help on close plays, as some players do. The man hit 573 major league home runs and no umpire ever swung a bat for him.|sign=[[Ron Luciano]]|source=Umpire Strikes Back, page 59<ref>{{cite book|title=Umpire Strikes Back|first=Ron|last=Luciano|publisher=Bantam|year=1984|isbn=978-0553248463|page=59}}</ref>}}

[[Image:MOA Killebrew chair1.JPG|thumb|Harmon Killebrew's red bleacher seat showing where his {{convert|520|ft|m|adj=on}} home run was hit, overlooking the flume ride at the [[Mall of America|MOA]]'s [[Nickelodeon Universe]] in Bloomington, Minnesota.]]
Killebrew was known for his quick hands and exceptional upper-body strength, demonstrated by several "tape measure" home runs that he hit in the prime of his career. Killebrew said that his first home run in the Majors was his favorite, coming off [[Billy Hoeft]] at [[Griffith Stadium]]. He said of it, "[[Frank House (baseball)|Frank House]] was the catcher. When I came to the plate, he said, 'Kid, we<U+2019>re going to throw you a fastball.' I didn<U+2019>t know whether to believe him or not. I hit it out. It was one of the longest home runs I ever hit. As I crossed the plate, House said, 'That<U+2019>s the last time I ever tell you what pitch is coming'."<ref name=Goldstein/>

On August 3, 1962, he was the first batter ever to hit a baseball over the left field roof at [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]], a seldom-reached target as contrasted with the old ballpark's smaller right field area. Only three others accomplished this feat during the next 37 seasons before the stadium was closed.<ref name="Pahigian">[[#Pahigian|Pahigian and O'Connell]], p. 253.</ref>
On May 24, 1964, Harmon hit the longest measured homer at [[Memorial Stadium (Baltimore)|Baltimore Memorial Stadium]], {{convert|471|ft|m}} to deep left center. The ball landed in the far reaches of the bleachers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=3409131|title=Baseball Today|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> The only player to hit one completely out of the Orioles' stadium was [[Frank Robinson]] in 1966; his blast was reported as about {{convert|451|ft|m}}, or about {{convert|20|ft|m}} less than Killebrew's hit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baseballlibrary.com/chronology/byyear.php?year=1966#May8|title=May 1966 Chronology|publisher=Baseball Library|accessdate=August 22, 2008}}</ref> On June 3, 1967, Killebrew hit a {{convert|520|ft|m|adj=on}} home run, the longest measured home run ever hit at Metropolitan Stadium and, as of 2011, the longest in Twins history.<ref name="Rushin1956"/><ref name="Leboutillier28">[[#Leboutillier|Leboutillier]], p. 28.</ref> That event is commemorated at the [[Mall of America]] in Bloomington, Minnesota, which includes a plaque marking home plate, and one red-painted seat from the Met which was placed at the location and elevation of the landing spot of the home run.<ref name="Rushin1956"/> The new Target Field has a statue of a Gold Glove outside Gate 34 and it is exactly {{convert|520|ft|m}} from Target Field's home plate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/arts/jean-gabler-harmon-killebrew-twins-say-goodbye|first=Jean|last=Gabler|title=Harmon Killebrew: The Minnesota Twins say goodbye to a legend|work=[[Twin Cities Daily Planet]]|date=June 15, 2011|accessdate=June 17, 2011}}</ref>
{{-}}

